                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-285-off1460 t18280911-285-victim1574"></join>
                     </persName>
                  , and fixed to a certain building; against the Statute
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-285-person1575">
                  CHARLES 
                  CAMANI
               <interp inst="t18280911-285-person1575" type="surname" value="CAMANI"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-285-person1575" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-285-person1575" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a porter in the employ of Mr. Kensington Lewis, of <placeName id="t18280911-285-crimeloc1462">St. James'-street, Piccadilly, in<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182809110151"></xptr>the parish of St. James'</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280911-285-crimeloc1462" type="placeName" value="St. James'-street, Piccadilly, in182809110151the parish of St. James'"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280911-285-crimeloc1462" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-285-off1460 t18280911-285-crimeloc1462"></join>. On the night of the 31st of July, when I went to shut up the shop, this brass was on the railing, and in the morning I missed it; I saw it again at Marlborough-street; I fitted it to the place - it fitted-exactly.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-285-person1576">
                  JOHN 
                  CAIN
               <interp inst="t18280911-285-person1576" type="surname" value="CAIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-285-person1576" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-285-person1576" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was on duty about half-past three o'clock in the morning in question - I saw the prisoner removing this brass - I went up to him, and he went away; I waited - he came again, and began again to take it up; I sprung my rattle, and he ran off, but we pursued and took him at the corner of Bury-street.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-285-person1577">
                  WILLIAM 
                  THOMPSON
               <interp inst="t18280911-285-person1577" type="surname" value="THOMPSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-285-person1577" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-285-person1577" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I assisted in taking the prisoner; I compared the brass - it fitted exactly.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-285-person1578">
                  THOMAS 
                  GOOK
               <interp inst="t18280911-285-person1578" type="surname" value="GOOK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-285-person1578" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-285-person1578" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I received charge of the prisoner, and fitted the brass to the rails.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. It was extreme poverty that drove me to it- I had no food for two days before.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280911-285-verdict1463" type="verdictDescription">
